HANTAVIRUS UPDATE 2008 - AMERICAS (13): PANAMA (LOS SANTOS)
***********************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

Date: Wed 6 Aug 2008
Source: Critica en linea [in Spanish, trans. & summ. Mod. TY, edited]
<http://www.critica.com.pa/archivo/08062008/prov01.html>


The death of a patient from a hantavirus [infection] was confirmed by the
regional health [office] of the Los Santos province in Panama. Information
from the Instituto Conmemorativo Gorgas provided details about the
death of a patient in the Anita Moreno hospital due to the illness
caused [by a virus] from rats [see list below].

The patient, approximately a month ago [July 2008] came to the
hospital with the symptoms of a severe cold. However, [the patient]
refused to allow x-rays to be taken and left the hospital. Later, [the
patient] returned to the hospital with much more acute clinical signs
and died in the hospital.

The victim, age 65 years, resided in the area of La Espigadilla de
Los Santos, and worked there as a mason, according to family members.

[Byline: Zenaida Vasquez]

--
Communicated by:
HealthMap alerts via
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The hantaviruses (and their rodent hosts) recognized in Panama
include Rio Segundo (_Reithrodontomys mexicanus_), Choclo
(_Oligoryzomys fulvescens (costaricensis)_), and Calabazo
(_Zygodontomys brevicauda (cherriei)_). Of these 3, only Choclo is a
known human pathogen, causing hantavirus pulmonary syndrome. ProMED
thanks Dr. James Mills for providing a current list of world-wide
hantaviruses and their reservoir hosts.

A map of Panama show Los Santos province in south-central Panama can
be accessed at:
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/americas/panama.jpg>. - Mod. TY]
